-- =============================================================================
-- Section 14: Consequences of LLPO
-- =============================================================================

-- LLPO implies that closed propositions are closed under finite disjunctions.
-- This is because LLPO is equivalent to the statement:
-- (¬¨P ‚ą® ¬¨Q) ‚ÜĒ ¬¨(P ‚ąß Q) for open P, Q

-- Given P, Q closed propositions:
-- P ‚ÜĒ ‚ąÄn. őĪn = 0, Q ‚ÜĒ ‚ąÄn. ő≤n = 0
-- We want: P ‚ą® Q is closed.
--
-- P ‚ą® Q ‚ÜĒ (‚ąÄn. őĪn = 0) ‚ą® (‚ąÄn. ő≤n = 0)
--
-- Define ő≥ : ‚Ąē‚ąě by: ő≥(2k) = őĪ(k), ő≥(2k+1) = ő≤(k)
-- (But ő≥ may hit 1 more than once if both őĪ and ő≤ hit 1.)
--
